pr_review_comment_body:
@azai91 not really. WriteInplace only works in a few operators (sum, activation, batchnorm). It doesn't work on some operators such as convolution and pooling for sure because the inputs and outputs of these operators don't have the same shape. 

Ideally, we should have two functions for this, so one of them have an interface consistent with `CreateMKLDNNWeightGrad` (creating MKLDNN memory from any NDArray, instead of just output NDArrays).

If you prefer to use one function, please update the comment and explain why `CreateMKLDNNMem` needs `in_arr`. Meanwhile, please rename `arr` of `CreateMKLDNNWeightGrad ` to `out_arr`, so `CreateMKLDNNMem` and `CreateMKLDNNWeightGrad` are still consistent.

I find the logic here a big confusing.  I'd prefer something more like

```python
single_query = None
if rewrite_inserts_single_query:
    single_query = self. _exec_single_query_insert(...)
if single_query:
    self.execute(single_query)
else:
    for parameters in seq_of_parameters:
        ...
```

This should be:
if firefox_binary_path:
More pythonic way...

I don't think there's any key that starts with `_` anymore.

It seems that `fdTools.py` is a trimmed down version of `ConvertFontToCID.py`. I've been working on that file to fix https://github.com/adobe-type-tools/afdko/issues/470, and this is how I rewrote `__repr__`:

```python
    def __repr__(self):
        fddict = {}
        for key, val in vars(self).items():
            if val is None:
                continue
            fddict[key] = val
        return "<%s '%s' %s>" % (
            self.__class__.__name__, fddict.get('DictName', 'no name'), fddict)
```

> ```css
> #markdown {
>  padding: 0.3em 0;
> }
> ```
I don't understand why you'd expect this to work? By default, `p` elements have padding; this reduces that padding. We're not trying to add padding to the parent container at all.

For convenience. It lets you write
```ts
addParams(base, {
  run: run,
  limit_attr_size: limit,
  large_attrs_key: limit ? '_key' : undefined,
})
```
which would otherwise have to be written as
```ts
const params = {};
params.run = run;
if (limit !== undefined) {
  params.limit_attr_size = limit.
  params.large_attrs_key = '_key';
}
addParams(base, params);
```
(Note that this filter was already present in `queryEncoder`; I didn't just decide to add it.)

There's a very common related pattern in React. In React, falsy elements are not rendered. So you can write
```jsx
render() {
  const loginEnabled: boolean = this.props.loginEnabled;
  return <div>
    <span>Hello!</span>
    {loginEnabled && <LoginButton />}
  </div>;
}
```
so if `loginEnabled` is `true` then a `LoginButton` will be rendered; otherwise, `false` will be rendered and so there will be no effect.

If I'm not mistaken, I think the logic in this function reduces to

```javascript
if (_.isEqual(lowerSteps, valueSteps) && _.isEqual(upperSteps, valueSteps) {
  return {
    seriesObject: tagsObject,
    valueSteps: valueSteps,
    lowerSteps: lowerSteps,
    upperSteps: upperSteps,
  };
}
return null;
```

I've pushed a commit to your branch that should get this working.  (Feel free to merge into your own commit). Description below.

The missing piece is that the current implementation is only half-updating the chain; `chain_start` is only used to generated the docstring, but the actual dispatch begins at the pointer stored inside the `rec_capsule` created by the code path when there is no existing chain:
initial definition a few lines above:
```C++
            capsule rec_capsule(rec, [](void *ptr) { // ...
            // ...

            m_ptr = PyCFunction_NewEx(rec->def, rec_capsule.ptr(), scope_module.ptr());
```
This `rec_capsule`, which points to the initial function, gets passed to the `dispatcher()` function as `self`; the dispatcher then starts the chain from that function record.

So in addition to setting `chain_start`, we're going to have to dig into that capsule and replace its pointer (but *without* destructing the capsule because destruction frees the chained function records).  This should do it:
```C++
            if (rec->is_prepended) {
                // Beginning of chain; we need to replace the capsule's current head-of-the-chain
                // pointer with this one, then make this one point to the previous head of the
                // chain.
                chain_start = rec;
                rec->next = chain;
                auto rec_capsule = reinterpret_borrow<capsule>(((PyCFunctionObject *) m_ptr)->m_self);
                rec_capsule.set_pointer(rec);
            } else {
```
which needs a new method `capsule::set_pointer` wrapping `PyCapsule_SetPointer`:

```C++
    // Replaces a capsule's pointer *without* calling the destructor on the existing one.
    void set_pointer(const void *value) {
        if (PyCapsule_SetPointer(m_ptr, const_cast<void *>(value)) != 0)
            pybind11_fail("Could not set capsule pointer");
    }
```
